sql:
SELECT segment_id, segment_name, segment_packet_loss
FROM network_segments
WHERE segment_packet_loss > (
  SELECT AVG(segment_packet_loss)
  FROM network_segments
);

SELECT performance_id, rate_r, rate_s, percent_loss
FROM network_performance
WHERE percent_loss > 0;

SELECT performance_id, duration, packets_per_ms, receivers, senders, rate_r, rate_s, percent_sent, percent_loss, segment_id, test_date, test_description, test_type
FROM network_performance
WHERE test_environment = 'staging' AND round = (SELECT MAX(round) FROM network_performance WHERE test_environment = 'staging');

SELECT DISTINCT users.user_id, users.user_name, users.email
FROM users
JOIN alert_recipients ON users.user_id = alert_recipients.user_id;

SELECT tag_name, COUNT(*) AS count
FROM performance_tags
GROUP BY tag_name;

external_knowledge:
;
Higher performance rates indicate more efficient data transmission;
Lower packet loss signifies a more stable network;
A segment with high performance rates and low packet loss is considered efficient;
This information helps in identifying well-performing network segments.

sql:
SELECT * 
FROM performance_notes 
WHERE created_at < '2023-05-01';

SELECT note_text, note_status
FROM performance_notes
WHERE created_at > '2023-05-02 12:00:00';

SELECT segment_id, segment_name, location
FROM network_segments
WHERE segment_packet_loss < 0.05;

external_knowledge:
- Serious issues refer to high-severity alerts; 
- Critical level in this context means the metric value is greater than 0.1 and the operator is set to '>';
- Major alerts are those with a high-severity level.
